"Dinezio P.N., Clement A., Vecchi G.A., Soden B., Broccoli A.J., Otto-Bliesner B.L., Braconnot P.","The response of the Walker circulation to Last Glacial Maximum forcing: Implications for detection in proxies",2011,"Paleoceanography","26","3", PA3217,"","",,,10.1029/2010PA002083,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052238288&partnerID=40&md5=4f4436b1883e0c5511320031753ca67a","Division of Meteorology and Physical Oceanography, RSMAS, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Geophyscial Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, NOAA, Princeton Forrestral, PO Box 308, Princeton, NJ 08542-0308, United States; Department of Environmental Sciences, Rutgers University, 14 College Farm Rd., New Brunswick, NJ 08901-8551, United States; Climate Change Research Section, CCR/CGD, NCAR, 1850 Table Mesa Dr., Boulder, CO 80307, United States; IPSL, Laboratoire de Sciences du Climat et de l'Fenvironnement, CEA Saclay, Orme des Merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette, France","Dinezio, P.N., Division of Meteorology and Physical Oceanography, RSMAS, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Clement, A., Division of Meteorology and Physical Oceanography, RSMAS, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Vecchi, G.A., Geophyscial Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, NOAA, Princeton Forrestral, PO Box 308, Princeton, NJ 08542-0308, United States; Soden, B., Division of Meteorology and Physical Oceanography, RSMAS, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Broccoli, A.J., Department of Environmental Sciences, Rutgers University, 14 College Farm Rd., New Brunswick, NJ 08901-8551, United States; Otto-Bliesner, B.L., Climate Change Research Section, CCR/CGD, NCAR, 1850 Table Mesa Dr., Boulder, CO 80307, United States; Braconnot, P., IPSL, Laboratoire de Sciences du Climat et de l'Fenvironnement, CEA Saclay, Orme des Merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette, France","The response of the Walker circulation to Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) forcing is analyzed using an ensemble of six coordinated coupled climate model experiments. The tropical atmospheric overturning circulation strengthens in all models in a manner that is dictated by the response of the hydrological cycle to tropical cooling. This response arises from the same mechanism that has been found to explain the weakening of the tropical circulation in response to anthropogenic global warming but with opposite sign. Analysis of the model differences shows that the ascending branch of the Walker circulation strengthens via this mechanism but vertical motion also weakens over areas of the Maritime Continent exposed due to lower sea level. Each model exhibits a different balance between these two mechanisms, and the result is a Pacific Walker circulation response that is not robust. Further, even those models that simulate a stronger Walker circulation during the LGM do not simulate clear patterns of surface cooling, such as La Nia-like cooling or enhanced equatorial cooling, as proposed by previous studies. In contrast, the changes in the Walker circulation have a robust and distinctive signature on the tilt of the equatorial thermocline, as expected from zonal momentum balance. The changes in the Walker circulation also have a clear signature on the spatial pattern of the precipitation changes. A reduction of the east-west salinity contrast in the Indian Ocean is related to the precipitation changes resulting from a weakening of the Indian Walker circulation. These results indicate that proxies of thermocline depth and sea surface salinity can be used to detect actual LGM changes in the Pacific and Indian Walker circulations, respectively, and help to constrain the sensitivity of the Walker circulation to tropical cooling. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"anthropogenic effect; climate forcing; climate modeling; cooling; ensemble forecasting; equatorial dynamics; global warming; hydrological cycle; hydrological response; La Nina; Last Glacial Maximum; marine atmosphere; momentum transfer; overturn; paleoatmosphere; precipitation intensity; proxy climate record; sea level; thermocline; vertical movement; Walker circulation; Indian Ocean; Pacific Ocean; Nia; Pomatiopsis californica",,,,,,"Andreasen, D.H., Ravelo, A.C., Tropical Pacific Ocean ther-mocline depth reconstructions for the Last Glacial Maximum (1997) Paleocea-nography, 12, pp. 395-414. , doi:10.1029/97PA00822; Andreasen, D.H., Ravelo, A.C., Broccoli, A.J., Remote forcing at the Last Glacial Maximum in the tropical Pacific Ocean (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106, pp. 879-897. , doi:10.1029/1999JC000087; Bakun, A., Weeks, S.J., The marine ecosystem off Peru: What are the secrets of its fishery productivity and what might its future hold? (2008) Prog. Oceanogr, 79, pp. 290-299. , doi:10.1016/j.pocean.2008.10.027; Braconnot, P., Otto-Bliesner, B., Harrison, S., Joussaume, S., Peterchmitt, J.-Y., Abe-Ouchi, A., Crucifix, M., Zhao, Y., Results of PMIP2 coupled simulations of the Mid-Holocene and last glacial maximum - Part 1: Experiments and large-scale features (2007) Climate of the Past, 3 (2), pp. 261-277; Broccoli, A.J., Tropical cooling at the last glacial maximum: An atmosphere-mixed layer ocean model simulation (2000) Journal of Climate, 13 (5), pp. 951-976; Broccoli, A.J., Dahl, K.A., Stouffer, R.J., Response of the ITCZ to Northern Hemisphere cooling (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett., 33, pp. L01702. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024546; Cane, M.A., Clement, A.C., Kaplan, A., Kushnir, Y., Pozdnyakov, D., Seager, R., Zebiak, S.E., Murtugudde, R., Twentieth century sea surface temperature trends (1997) Science, 275, pp. 957-960. , doi:10.1126/science. 275.5302.957; Chiang, J.C.H., Bitz, C.M., Influence of high latitude ice cover on the marine Intertropical Convergence Zone (2005) Clim. Dyn., 25, pp. 477-496. , doi:10.1007/s00382-005-0040-5; Clarke, A.J., Analytical the